@ciaralondon @yashgodiwala ok so TL;DR: there are a ton of drugs/nanoparticles that adhere to mucus, which makes them pretty hard to deliver to tissues that are mucus-coated like the eye, intestinal epithelium, etc. So the Justin Hanes lab at JHU got to thinking about how to deal with this, and they're very good at working with PEG which is a hydrophilic polymer. People knew that a large PEG coating (10 kDa) slows down mucus penetration because the long strands of PEG tangle up with the mucus polymer mesh, so everyone generally thought that that would hold true for all PEG coatings. But the Hanes lab realized "oh wait, we can model this like diffusion of polymers through a polymer mesh", where the smaller the diffusing polymer -> the faster the diffusion. On top of that, they realized that by coating the adhesive nanoparticles at high density, they could block off all the space for adhesive interactions between the mucus mesh and the drug/particle itself. So they tried out a high-density, low molecular weight (2 kDa) PEG coating and it worked out great. Steroids are hydrophobic, so a very good model system & candidate to carry forward; eventually, steroid nanoparticles coated with 2 kDa high density PEG became Eysuvis for dry eye 😄

not a shocking leap in human ability, but a creative & fundamentally solid application of known technologies to both understand new science (diffusion dynamics in mucus) and develop a clinically relevant therapeutic

It comes down to having an "attention" mechanism. CNNs  and their recurrent variants don't selectively attend to every part of an input sequence due to dimensionality contstraints, so problems that require pattern matching across a large manifold fair much better with transformers (i.e. Natural language processing with long paragraphs, protein folding with millions of interaction sites, etc...)
